Just wanted to give my two cents on the idea of intelligence. There are so many types of intelligence but when people talk about being smart it's almost always in relation with academics. And academic intelligence has a lot of the aspects that are tested and reflected in a person's IQ.

But like I said there are so many types. I'm lucky to have pretty good academic intelligence plus some street smarts. But I've always admired Jack for his emotional intelligence. He's able to communicate his emotions, thoughts, and ideas so easily. I figure he could maintain an intellectual conversation on certain social topics quite well, whereas I struggle to explain and articulate my thoughts (but writing them is easier than a fast-paced situation like talking).

ALSO to those students out there who feel stupid, or people like my friends who are like "naw I'm too dumb for university/college". Education is not only for the highly intelligent. Postsecondary success depends more on your time management, ability to cope, study strategies, and motivation than any sort of academic intelligence. From my experience, academic intelligence allows people to learn concepts faster, but that doesn't mean most people can't learn those concepts too. The majority who go on to a successful career are individuals who put in the effort and time required to get there. Not the people with the highest IQs.

Thanks for coming to my Ted Talk.

snippet.textDisplay:
Things to keep in mind when your in a low:
1) People love you, be it your family or friends or some stranger that says hi to you on the bus when you see each other. You WILL be missed.

2) Your emotions are all valid. How you react to things, while maybe not 100% reasonable, is still valid. There is always a reason why you react the way you do.

3) Sadness is NOT a weakness. It is a very natural emotion. It is okay to be sad and very okay to talk about being sad. I have lost two amazing young men because of the stigma that talking about feelings makes you weak. It does NOT. Tell someone, express yourself and if they wont listen find someone who will.

4) You are NOT your mental illness. It does NOT define you. You define you.

5) Every little thing you manage to do when in a low is worth celebrating. You woke up, awesome you didnt sleep all day! You only managed to eat somd crackers, Awesome you ate something! You watched tv all day, Awesome you got out of bed!

6) Its okay to not have the energy to so much as take a shower. The war in your head is exhausting, have a lazy day or two. Its okay and you needed the rest.

7) Its okay to ask for help. Admiting you need help is the first step to recovery. It is a very difficult step to make and anyone who struggles with mental illness understands just how hard.

Just wanted to share, its not a happy story but I need to get it out. I'm also not looking for sympathy, god knows I've had my share. This happened ages ago now, but during the loss question I got a very strong flash back to it. My mom had been suffering from stage 4 lung cancer for a year or so at this point and it had long since spread to an inoperable part of her brain. Lungs dont have pain sensors and whatnot so it wasnt caught until it had spread. Nothing had seem to be working and the medical system kind of gave up. Feburary 13 2006 I was in grade 9, and it was English. We were working on some sort of project and suddenly the office called the classroom. I noticed my teacher glance at me and I knew. As soon as she said my name and told me my step dad was waiting for me at the office, everyone in the class knew as well. We were in a small town and my mom was well loved so it wasnt a secret she was battling cancer. Its been so long but every so often it still hits like a tsunami. Valentines day became a horrible day for me, it was a set reminder of my loss that I couldnt hide from. Hearts would start popping up everywhere and I'd be taken right back. Some losses never go away, you just get better at swimming in the storm. I can now say that my mom died and its just a fact, but every so often things come up and the emotions come flooding back.
Thank you anyone who reads this. Again I am not looking for sympathy, just needed to share so I didnt dwell on it too long. And if this can help anyone else struggling with a severe loss its worth it. If anyone is struggling to cope I am willing to listen and just a pm away.

When he talked about his grandma I honestly felt that. I've only ever wanted to cry at two funerals. That honestly saying something because the first funeral I went to was younger than five. In 2019 alone I went to three. So when he was talking about "should I be feeling this" "should I be crying?" I honestly felt that.
And, when he was talking about how taking care of yourself can be labeled as selfish, that is something that I just recently learned the hard way. I was neglected, verbally, and emotionally abused and had to watch my mother go through drug addiction and an abusive relationship that she still hasn't gotten out of today. A few months ago I realized that I was still being abused, emotional abuse is really hard to label, and because of gaslighting, I've genuinely questioned if any of my memories are real because my mom and her boyfriend used to tell me that I'm crazy and that I just imagined all of it. Recently I learned to take care of myself, I went to a hospital, got on medication for my depression, anxiety, suicidal thoughts, got meds to help with my nightmares from PTSD, and I moved out of my mom's house. When I did, my mom told me I was selfish, because I told her that I wasn't safe there, around him, and that I felt that he was still abusing us and that if I stayed there I would end up dead. So this video hit home with me and hearing that he was thinking like "would anyone even miss me?" I got a little mad because while I was living there, his videos literally got me to throw away a suicide note. This happens a few times. I've seen so many comments like mine saying that he saved them, and I wonder if he knew that and knew the number of people that his videos and he saved, he maybe would have been a little prouder, knowing that he has done so much good as to literally save lives.

I attempted suicide in September 2018. For me the whole thing about it creating pain for people is kinda bs for my situation. Everyone ignored me whenever I showed signs, when I talked to my religious gma all they did was pray over me and leave it alone, my mom was to busy for me and my dad isn't good with this stuff. My parents were upset, SOME family came to the hospital (i was in immediate care for 5 days and the psych place for a week). Then after I got out everybody pretended like it didn't happen :(. People (for me) say that they're there, but when you need them they're nowhere to be found, or they are one of the people talking shit on you. It didn't seem to matter to anyone except for me.

Literally the only thing 100% successful at keeping me from doing it again are the fucking bills that I got from it. I live in America so it's like "Fuck you if you're depressed. You now have hospital bills that make you want to attempt suicide again".
Example: They put down the wrong insurance when billing me for the ambulance ride, so it registered as no insurance. I would've had to pay almost $900 for an ambulance ride..

I cannot relate to the story about your grandmother more. When my grandma died almost the exact same thing happened to me. I had a pretty close relationship with my grandma. She lived just around the block and had been a big part of the family since I was a wee boy. But I have to confess something that has haunted me for years... When my Dad pulled me into the living room and said that my grandma died, he burst into tears (I had only seen him cry maybe once before), my sister burst into tears, and I think my mom did too... I didn't. I don't know what to make of it, I don't know why it happened, but I smiled.

I didn't feel happy, I didn't feel sad, I don't think I knew what to feel. But I smiled. I clapped a hand over my mouth as fast as I could so that no one saw it, but it has hung over me ever since then. Why did I smile?

And I know a lot of others feel the same way. I'm almost certain I'm not the only life you've saved.
